The governor of Enugu State, Ifeanyi Ugwuanyi has appealed to the federal government for more ecological interventions in the State given its numerous environmental challenges. He stated this in Udi during the commissioning and handing over ceremony of flood and erosion control project at Federal Road Safety Corps (FRSC) Academy, Enugu State. Ugwuanyi who was represented by the Commissioner for Transport, Hon. M. J. Ekweremadu thanked the federal government for the timely intervention in the academy. The project was one of the 23 ecological intervention projects approved by President Muhammadu Buhari for the second quarter of 2018. In his address, the deputy chairman, House Committee on Ecological Fund, Hon. Abdullahi Mammud urged the people to take ownership of the project, maintain it and ensure its sustainability. He pointed out that with the completion of the project, that the devastating effects of flooding and erosion menace within the Academy and its environs would be a thing of the past. Also speaking, the permanent secretary of EFO, Dr Hadiza Lawal, Dr. Habiba Lawal lauded the project contractor and consultant for the timely completion of the project, emphasizing that it would prevent further environmental degradation, loss of lives and properties. Lawal who was represented by EFO’s deputy director of Soil Erosion and Flood Control Department, Mr. Mathias Eluma, noted that the project was initiated through a request for an urgent intervention, that  was forwarded to the EFO by the Commandant of FRSC on the need to arrest the continuous flood and erosion menace in the Corps Academy, Udi. 